{
  "texts": [
    "Intuitively, policy convergence whereby",
    "x for some x could never be an equilibrium.",
    "Such a point would deviate from the ideal point of at least one of the two parties, say party R, and if this party moved towards its ideal point, this would have a second-order cost in terms of vote shares as derived in (1), but would always have a first-order gain in terms of moving closer to one's own ideal point.",
    "While the existence of an anti-symmetric Nash equilibrium is immediate (from a straightforward application of Brouwer's fixed point theorem given the continuity of vote shares in (1)), uniqueness is not guaranteed, because the trade-off-between being close to one's ideal point and gaining more votes from (1)-is often non-convex.",
    "However, there can only be a finite number of symmetric Nash equilibria, and hence the existence of an extremal one is also guaranteed, as stated in part (ii)."
  ]
}